Information

These are the exercises for Linear Regression in R course of the Public Health Sciences Course Program at the University of Bern.

The pipe operator is written as %>% or |>, and it takes the result of the expression on its left and passes it as the first argument to the function on its right. In other words, it allows you to apply a series of functions to a data object step by step.

Before starting the exercises, you should run the setup chunk at least once.

10 %>% 
  + 5 %>% 
  - 2
[1] 13

Data visualizations and model assumptions

It is always recommended to visualize your data before you run any kind of analysis.

Exercise 3

Plot the fev1 and height as histograms and inspect their distributions.
Use ggplot() and geom_histogram().

Code 
plot_height <- perulung %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = fev1)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30,
                 fill = "steelblue", 
                 color = "grey") +
  theme_bw()


plot_fev1 <- perulung %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30,
                 fill = "steelblue", 
                 color = "grey") +
  theme_bw()


grid.arrange(plot_height, plot_fev1, ncol = 2)

Exercise 3

Plot lung function fev1 and height in a scatter plot.
Use ggplot() and geom_point.

Code

  ggplot(aes(x = height, y = fev1)) +
  geom_point(color = "steelblue") +
  theme_bw()

Least squares estimation (LSE)

Exercise 5

Calculate the regression coefficients \(\hat{b1}\) and \(\hat{b0}\) according to slide 13 and given that:

x = perulung$height
y = perulung$fev1

Use cor(), sd() and mean().

Code 
b1 = (cor(y, x) * sd(y)) / sd(x)
b0 = mean(y) - b1 * mean(x)


cat("b1:", b1,"b0:", b0)
b1: 0.03111954 b0: -2.265817

Exercise 6

Use the function lm() to preform a simple linear regression. This will apply the method of least squares to fit regression line.
Use summary() to inspect your results.
Are your calculated \(\hat{b1}\) and \(\hat{b0}\) the same as the ones from lm()?

model_1 <- lm(fev1 ~ height, data = perulung)
summary(model_1)

Exercise 7

Given your fitted regression, what is the the predicted fev1 of a child that is 113.8 cm tall?
Try to calculate it with \(\hat{b0}\) + \(\hat{b1}\) or predict().
What happens if you predict with a value that was not originally in the range of the data frame?

Code 
# Y = b0 + b1*X
Y = b0 + b1 * 113.8

# Predict
Y_predict = predict(model_1, newdata = data.frame(height = 113.8))

cat("Y:",Y ,"Y_predict:", Y_predict)
Y: 1.275586 Y_predict: 1.275586

Exercise 10

Use the estimate and the std.error saved in your model summary.
Compare your results to the p.value of your fitted regression.

Code 
t_test <- summary_model_1$estimate / summary_model_1$std.error

p <- 2*pt(-abs(t_test), components_model_1$df.residual)

Exercise 11

Normalize fev1 and height ((i - mean(i)) / sd(i)) and re-run lm() with them. This way you can verify that the fitted slope is the same as the correlation in Exercise 4.

y_norm <- (y - mean(y)) / sd(y)

cor(x_norm, y_norm, method = c("pearson"))

Multiple linear regression

Including multiple independent variables

We will now examine a data set that includes the birth weight of children.
The data was collected in 1986 at Baystate Medical Center in Springfield, Massachusetts. More information on the variables you find here.

# Rename the columns to have more descriptive names
birthwt <- MASS::birthwt %>%
  rename(birthweight_below_2500 = low,
         mother_age = age,
         mother_weight = lwt,
         ethnicity = race,
         mother_smokes = smoke,
         previous_prem_labor = ptl,
         hypertension = ht,
         uterine_irr = ui,
         physician_visits = ftv,
         birthweight = bwt)

# Recode the factors
birthwt <- birthwt %>% 
  mutate(birthweight_below_2500 = factor(birthweight_below_2500, levels = c(0,1), labels=c("no","yes")),
         ethnicity = factor(ethnicity, levels = c(1,2,3), labels=c("White","Black", "Other")),
         mother_smokes = factor(mother_smokes, levels = c(0,1), labels=c("no","yes")),
         hypertension = factor(hypertension, levels = c(0,1), labels=c("no","yes")),
         uterine_irr = factor(uterine_irr, levels = c(0,1), labels=c("no","yes")))
                    
birthwt %>%

Create a multiple linear regression model with birthweight as the outcome. Include mother_smokes, mother_age, mother_weight and hypertension.

model_full <- lm(formula = birthweight ~ mother_smokes + mother_age + mother_weight + hypertension, data = birthwt)

F-test

Exercise 13

Test if model_full or model_reduced explains more of the variance of birthweight?

model_reduced <- lm(formula = birthweight ~ mother_smokes + mother_weight, data = birthwt)

The anova function compares the two models and calculates the F-statistic and p-value to determine whether the full model (model_full) explains significantly more variance than the reduced model (model_reduced). Explain your outcome in a sentence.

Code 
anova(model_full, model_reduced)

Model 1: birthweight ~ mother_smokes + mother_age + mother_weight + hypertension
Model 2: birthweight ~ mother_smokes + mother_weight

Code 
# We conclude that the more complex model is significantly (p = 0.02162) better than the simpler model, and thus we favor the more complex model.

Residual analysis

For a quick look at the the models residuals we can use plot().

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(model_full)

However we can use the package performance to analyse our model in depth. We can use check_model to see if our residuals are normally distributed. Is the line more or less flat?

check_model <- check_model(model_full, panel = FALSE, check = "linearity")
plot(check_model) 
$NCV

Exercise 14

Use check_normality to see if our residuals are normally distributed. Note that this formal test almost always yields significant results for the distribution of residuals and visual inspection (e.g.Â Q-Q plots) are preferable.

Code 
normality_result <- check_normality(model_full)
normality_result
OK: residuals appear as normally distributed (p = 0.427).

Try to plot the QQ-plot of your normality_result with plot(). Do the dots follow the line?

Code 
plot(normality_result, type = "qq")

Heteroscedasticity

Exercise 15

Use check_heteroscedasticity to test significance for linear regression models. We assume that the model errors (or residuals) have constant variance. If this assumption is violated the p-values from the model are no longer reliable.

Code 
heteroscedasticity_result <- check_heteroscedasticity(model_full)
heteroscedasticity_result
OK: Error variance appears to be homoscedastic (p = 0.621).

Plot the heteroscedasticity_result with plot().

Code 
plot(heteroscedasticity_result)

Multicollinearity (variance inflation factor)

Exercise 17

Collinearity or multicollinearity is a problem that can occur in regression analysis when independent variables are highly correlated with each other. It can cause instability in the model results and make the model less accurate. By using vif() we can see if there are any problematic variables based on VIF.

Code 
vif(model_full)
mother_smokes    mother_age mother_weight  hypertension 
     1.003834      1.038703      1.100359      1.063673
